answers.text:
It's been a while, but I just wanted to check in on this thread again. At Civic Commons we're trying to better catalog open source projects by and for governments - particularly cities. Over time some of these have been listed on our wiki at  http://wiki.civiccommons.org/Civic_Software  &  http://wiki.civiccommons.org/Open_Source_Case_Studies  but we now have a beta version of a catalog called the Civic Commons Marketplace which makes it much easier to browse and share projects:  http://marketplace.civiccommons.org 
One thing we're trying to find are good examples of software projects that have been started by one government and then used or contributed to by other governments. Some examples of this include  http://opentripplanner.com  and  http://www.onebusaway.org  but we're looking for others so please let us know if you're aware of good examples. 
@Dan Schmick - we'd love to add your project to our catalog so others can benefit from it. Even if you think it's rough around the edges, that's better than nothing and we can help make it ready for reuse 
@Jack Pond - I think people are wiser and things have come a long way since the sad Peter Quinn story. Microsoft develops and supports open source software for government (http://ogdi.codeplex.com) and the White House now releases open source projects (http://civiccommons.org/2011/05/it-dashboard-six-weeks-in/)


